The obtained a-AuNPs were dropped on tin-foil wafers to prepare SERS substrates. The SEM image indicate that most of the a-AuNPs maintain the morphologies on the tin-foil wafer (Fig. S2). As the obtained a-AuNPs exhibit strong LSPR absorption at around 640 nm, the SERS performance of the substrate was evaluated comprehensively under the irradiation of a commonly used laser of 633 nm, using CV as the target molecule. Before the investigation, the amount of a-AuNPs on the tin-foil wafers was optimized firstly. As shown in Fig. 2
                     a, changing the loading amount of a-AuNPs on the tin-foil wafer does not affect the shape of the SERS spectrum of CV. No matter the loading amount of a-AuNPs, all the main characteristic Raman peaks of CV can be well detected from the obtained substrates (Table 1
                     ). However, the loading amount of a-AuNPs significantly affects the intensity of the main characteristic peaks. Taking the characteristic peak at 1618 cm−1 as an example, it reaches the strongest when the loading amount of a-AuNPs on the tin-foil wafer is 2.1 mg/mL, but decreases gradually when the loading amount either increases or decreases (Fig. 2b). Therefore, the SERS substrates used in the subsequent experiments were obtained by loading 2.1 mg/mL of a-AuNPs on the tin-foil wafers.
